# Co-creation

![](data:image/png;base64,)

## Overview
Co-creation is a principle, tactic, and tool used in public and social innovation work that involves collaborating with stakeholders, particularly those who are directly affected by the issue or problem being addressed.

## Purpose
The purpose of co-creation is to ensure that solutions are people-centered and meet the needs of all parties involved. It aims to create value through collaboration and mutual understanding between different actors.

## How it works
Co-creation involves working closely with stakeholders, including community members, experts, and other relevant parties, to design and implement solutions. This can involve joint planning, decision-making, and problem-solving activities that foster a sense of ownership and shared responsibility among all participants.

## Requirements
To effectively use co-creation, it is essential to have a willingness to collaborate, listen actively, and be open to new ideas and perspectives. A safe and inclusive environment should also be created to facilitate free-flowing communication and idea-sharing.

## Reflections
Co-creation requires patience, empathy, and a deep understanding of the needs and concerns of all stakeholders involved. It is essential to recognize that co-creation is not a one-time event but rather an ongoing process that requires continuous engagement and adaptation.

## Related methods (if any)
Co-creation is often used in conjunction with other social innovation methods, such as ethnography, ethics, and design thinking.

## License
The license for co-creation is generally free or open, allowing it to be adapted and applied in various contexts without restrictions.

## Examples
Examples of co-creation in practice include participatory budgeting initiatives, community-led planning processes, and collaborative research projects that involve stakeholders from diverse backgrounds.
